        {
          "username": "Summer Rosario",
          "rating": 2,
          "contributor_id": "110647403253629209950",
          "user_review_count": 3,
          "user_photo_count": 0,
          "user_thumbnail": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjUEzDgmY0MAMDdNgszxj57nL9Au3gwAGSQ5jKiLDkmqm151YKl7=s120-c-rp-mo-br100",
          "description": "I am so sad to write another review since my first one was a glowing 5 stars. As many good experiences I had with NYU, I am beyond disappointed with my recent, and last, experience that I had with them. After surgery in February, I was feel awful in March. I was presenting with all symptoms for my chronic disease, including bleeding and abdominal pain. I went back to NYU and was almost immediately dismissed. Told to follow-up outpatient with my surgeon and GI doctor. I messaged my surgeon, Dr. Simon, whose team redirected me to Dr. Chang, my GI doctor. No tests were ordered; Dr. Chang is prideful of her intelligence, I assume, because she was able to diagnose my symptoms as the very disease that I've had for 12 years and just had surgery for weeks ago. Instead of tests or any in-person follow-up, I was seen for 10 minutes virtually and prescribed Prednisone. I messaged Dr. Chang a week later as I couldn't keep food down. I was vomitting everything I ate and the pain was worse. Again, no in-person follow-up occurred, and this time, not even a virtual visit. Instead, she prescribed an additional medication and sent me on my merry way. After trying NYU's emergency room once more, and being entirely dismissed, I made my way to Mount Sinai. I presented my symptoms and they immediately ordered a scope and an MRI. Lo and behold, it turns out that the disease I was suffering from was at Mayo Score 3 (the most severe it can be) with SEVERE COLON DISTENTION!! I ended up at Mount Sinai for 3 weeks as I ended up needed emergency inpatient surgery because of how severe the disease was. Also, my CURRENT surgeon at Mount Sinai (who I will 100% recommend to anyone over ANY NYU doctor or surgeon) told me that the surgery was difficult because it turns out that Dr. Simon's work was sloppy and left me with so much scarring that turned a 4-5 hour surgery, into an 8 hour surgery. My current surgeon said the scarring was so bad that the team was very close to having to open me up completely rather than doing everything lapriscopically (which didn't happen, thankfully). I am beyond disappointed with NYU and their lack of compassion and ability. Neither time I went to their ER did a proper evaluation ensure. No scope or scan was done, no blood work was properly worked up. Their dismissal of my situation could have killed me had I not been pestering different hospital systems. I will forever be grateful for Mount Sinai for literally saving my life and taking me seriously over NYU, where they would have let me die rather than do their jobs properly. Safe to say my previous 5 stars has been balled up and trashed and burned. I would not recommend NYU for many things. Unless you are presenting something at surface level, don't expect anyone to listen to you or help you. Please advocate for yourself! If you KNOW something is not right, please speak up. Find another hospital that will take you seriously!",
          "link": "https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sCi9DQUlRQUNvZENodHljRjlvT21OU2NrSTBUVGxPTkZSU2RWZExOR3RaTm1GS1FuYxAB!2m1!1s0x0:0x4a856670ae2ae3c2!3m1!1s2@1:CAIQACodChtycF9oOmNSckI0TTlONFRSdVdLNGtZNmFKQnc%7C%7C?hl=en",
          "date": "a month ago",
